UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2070
1 school districts shall receive funds based on the average number of preschool
2 children being served on December 1 and March 1 of the prior academic year who
3 are appropriately identified as:
4 (a) Three (3) and four (4) years of age with disabilities; and
5 (b) Four (4) years of age[ identified as at risk of educational failure].
6 Local school districts may develop cooperative arrangements with other school
7 districts or organizations in accordance with KRS 157.280.
8 (6)[(4)] A child shall be eligible for a free and appropriate preschool education and
9 related services if:
10 (a) 1. The child has been identified as a child with a disability in accordance
11 with the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act, 20 U.S.C.
12 sec.[secs.] 1400 et seq.; or
13 2. The child has been identified in accordance with the definitions and
14 procedures for exceptional children and youth in accordance with KRS
15 157.200(1)(a) to (m); and
16 (b) The child is three (3) or four (4) years of age[:
17 1. By October 1, for any year before 2017; or
18 2. ] by August 1[, for 2017 or any year thereafter].
19 (7)[(5)] The chief state school officer shall receive and review proposals from local
20 school districts for grants to operate or oversee the operation of developmentally
21 appropriate preschool education programs. Districts may submit proposals for
22 implementing new services, enhancing existing preschool education services, or
23 contracting for services. In designing a local early childhood education program,
24 each district shall work with existing preschool programs to avoid duplication of
25 programs and services, to avoid supplanting federal funds, and to maximize Head
26 Start funds in order to serve as many four (4) year old children as possible.
27 (8)[(6)] Each program proposal shall include, at a minimum:
