1 (9)[(7)] If the superintendent and local Head Start director are unable to reach an
2 agreement on whether a Head Start program is fully utilized, the superintendent or
3 local Head Start director shall notify the chief state school officer. The local Head
4 Start director shall provide the chief state school officer all information relevant to
5 the utilization of the Head Start program. Within thirty (30) days of notification
6 from the superintendent or local Head Start director, the chief state school officer
7 shall make a determination of whether a Head Start program is fully utilized and
8 may execute the certification required by subsection (8)(q)[(6)(q)] of this section on
9 behalf of the local Head Start director.
10 (10)[(8)] Programs shall reflect an equitable geographic distribution representative of
11 all areas of the Commonwealth.
12 SECTION 3. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 157 IS CREATED TO
13 READ AS FOLLOWS:
14 (1) To increase preschool enrollment eligibility, each local school district shall work
15 with Head Start and other existing preschool programs to avoid duplication of
16 services and programs, to avoid supplanting federal funds, and to maximize Head
17 Start funds in order to serve as many four (4) year old children as possible, and
18 shall maintain certification from the Head Start director that the Head Start
19 program is fully utilized. If a local school district fails to comply with the
20 requirements of this subsection, the commissioner of education shall withhold
21 preschool funding for an amount equal to the number of Head Start-eligible
22 children served in the district who would have been eligible to be served by Head
23 Start under the full utilization certification required under this subsection. The
24 commissioner of education shall resolve any disputes and make a determination
25 of the district's compliance with the full utilization requirement.
26 (2) By March 1, 2028, a local school district shall prepare and submit a preschool
27 expansion plan to the Kentucky Department of Education for review and
Page 9 of 12
XXXX 2/4/2026 6:36 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2070
1 approval. Preschool expansion plans may include:
2 (a) The estimated school year when expansion will begin;
3 (b) The existing number of preschool students as of the date of plan
4 submission;
5 (c) The anticipated number of seats needed to enroll all four (4) year old
6 children in the district;
7 (d) The identification of any anticipated implementation and compliance
8 issues;
9 (e) A statement of intent regarding use of teaming partners for implementation;
10 (f) Any infrastructure and facility needs;
11 (g) Any transportation concerns;
12 (h) Any space or capacity concerns;
13 (i) Any anticipated facility, transportation, personnel, or other waivers needed
14 for expansion implementation, if any; and
15 (j) Any additional information as required by the department.
16 (3) (a) By December 1, 2027, the department shall promulgate administrative
17 regulations in accordance with KRS Chapter 13A to establish:
18 1. Procedures for school districts to submit preschool expansion
19 implementation plans to the department for review and approval;
20 2. Procedures and requirements for school districts to contract with
21 teaming partners to provide preschool education programs or services
22 for eligible children;
23 3. Requirements for school districts to proceed with preschool expansion
24 without the use of teaming partners, including documentation
25 certifying that teaming partners do not exist in the school district,
26 cannot meet the requirements of the program guidelines established in
27 administrative regulation, or choose not to participate;
Page 10 of 12
XXXX 2/4/2026 6:36 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2070
1 4. Procedures for school districts to submit preschool expansion program
2 waivers to the department for review and approval;
3 5. Procedures for a school district to apply for preschool expansion
4 funds following submission and approval of its preschool expansion
5 plan, including the creation of a uniform application form and
6 application review guidelines;
7 6. Procedures for review and approval of a school district’s application
8 for preschool expansion funds;
9 7. Procedures and criteria to be used by the department to distribute
10 preschool expansion funds to approved school districts through a
11 grant allotment system; and
12 8. Any additional administrative regulations necessary to effectuate this
13 section.
14 (b) When promulgating administrative regulations under this section, the
15 department shall consider standards and procedures that have been found
16 to be best practices relative to the regulation of preschool education
17 programs or services for children.
18 (4) By December 1, 2028, and each year thereafter, the department shall submit a
19 report to the Legislative Research Commission regarding preschool expansion for
20 referral to the appropriate Interim Joint Committee on Education. The purpose
21 of the annual report is to guide the General Assembly in expanding preschool
22 access in a phased and responsible manner. The report submitted by the
23 department shall include:
24 (a) A summary of the information provided by local school districts in their
25 respective preschool expansion plans;
26 (b) An assessment of:
27 1. The current state of preschool education programs or services in the
Page 11 of 12
XXXX 2/4/2026 6:36 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2070
1 Commonwealth of Kentucky; and
2 2. The ability of four (4) year old children in all areas of the state to
3 access preschool education programs or services;
4 (c) Any recommendations for the continued expansion of preschool access in
5 the Commonwealth of Kentucky;
6 (d) Any recommended additions or revisions to this chapter; and
7 (e) Any other data or information requested by the Legislative Research
8 Commission relating to the preschool education programs or services and
9 this chapter.
10 (5) The General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky recognizes the
11 importance of preschool education programs for children. It is the intent of the
12 General Assembly to expand access to preschool education and services to all
13 four (4) year old children in the Commonwealth of Kentucky, and such
14 expansion shall occur in a phased and responsible manner based on program
15 enrollment growth and available funding.
